      "instructions": "You should spend about 20 minutes on Questions 1–34, which are based on the passage below.",
      "passage": {
        "subtitle": "The History of Tea",
        "blocks": [
          { "label": "A", "text": "Tea was first consumed in ancient China, where its leaves were dried and steeped in hot water. Early records describe it primarily as a medicinal drink rather than a daily beverage." },
          { "label": "B", "text": "As overland and maritime trade routes opened, tea spread westward. Merchants carried it along caravan roads and later by sea, and demand grew quickly in Europe." },
          { "label": "C", "text": "Today tea is one of the most widely consumed drinks in the world, sold in supermarkets everywhere and produced on large commercial estates." },
          { "label": "D", "text": "Processing tea involves several careful steps, from withering the freshly picked leaves to heating them to halt oxidation before packaging." },
          { "label": "E", "text": "On a typical estate, buildings are arranged around a central yard, with a warehouse for storage and a separate shed used for drying the leaves." }
        ]
      },
